I truly like Lewis films when he can mix seriousness with comedy, he can be a capable fighter are deep sea diver and at the same time make it funny. Filling a film with nothing but slap stick gets old fast, but Lewis pulled off just the right amount of silly in this one. I won't reveal any spoilers other than the fact that the story of him getting off the Island and not being awarded a metal for capturing all the Japanize on the island was never really addressed and the only let down of the film.

Looking back on the sans-Dino body of work of Jerry Lewis. it's easy to sieze upon the "little boy" schtick he frequently used and call it cliché. But that's a cop-out because some form of it has always been a legitimate comedy trick in film. And it's been done more recently, from Mad TV's "Stewart" sketches as done by Michael McDonald to the SNL classic "Simon" as done by Mike Myers. And Lewis never fails to satisfy here as an immature and inept Naval officer, Lieutenant John Paul Steckler, heir of a long family tradition of nautical bumblers. But the latest Steckler has topped 'em all--try commanding a destroyer escort but, when it's time to muster out at the end of the war, losing track of the ship. It shows up on the inventory of "equipment not returned". Now he's going to have to pay for it. But the Navy does have a heart after all and assigns to Steckler a psychologist, Ensign Rita Benson (Dina Merrill) to help him remember what might have happened to the ship. The first attempt is hilarious when she puts him under hypnosis and takes him all the way back to what happened to a toy boat he was playing with in the bathtub when he was little. Another dilemma they have to deal with is when Benson meets Steckler's wife Prudence (Diana Spencer), who's just as childish as he is and immediately jealous of her husband's lovely therapist. Geez, and modern-day HBO viewers think Tony Soprano's shrink is a babe! But Benson, having no designs on Steckler, knows how to deal with her gently. And, since this is after all a comedy, the main problem works out well in the end. I'm not giving the ending away, but today's viewer, cynical enough about Government to imply that it's a four-letter word (GOVT), will appreciate the irony involved.

"Don't Give Up the Ship" is another Jerry Lewis golden oldie. This film seemed to be one of the more mellow Lewis classics, but it fit his style perfectly. I was able to feel his anxiety and frustration in most, if not all, of the scenes as his ability shined through.  Besides the content, the new mastering of the film in HD from a 4K scan was excellent- an extremely clear black and white picture. This is a keeper for Jerry Lewis fans.

Unlike The Nutty Professor, considered by many to be Jerry's best film, this movie has a considerably weaker plot, with just married naval officer Jerry flipping back and forth between his attempt at having a honeymoon and his efforts to locate a WWII ship that disappeared under his command. Joke lines are extremely corny, even for Jerry Lewis, perhaps suited to Jerry's audiences in 1959, but boring and silly today. Die hard Jerry Lewis fans may like this movie, but doubtful that it would hold the interest of the average classic comedy movie aficionado.
One of Jerry's first movies on his own and has a good story line. Funny in places, B&W came out great.

This black and white 1959  film, allegedly based on a true incident, takes a humorous look at the Navy. The story line is about a ship that has been "lost" and the officer responsible for it before it went missing. An inquiry is scheduled and the hunt begins; I won't spoil the story for those who haven't seen it, but if you decide to purchase it, you will find it entertaining. Notable supporting actors are Dina Merrill, Robert Middleton, Gale Gordon, Claude Akins, Mabel Albertson, Diana Spencer, and Mickey Shaughnessy.  It is a typical Jerry Lewis vehicle, leaving nothing out as far as comedic situations, dialog and stunts are concerned.  While I am not a Jerry Lewis fan, I enjoyed this and I did laugh a lot; Lewis is a master at his craft and I think this is one of his all over best comedies.

The DVD has simply designed front and back covers with all the right information; no frills on the inside. The film runs 99 minutes and is extremely  clear; good b/w tonal differentiation and no imperfections.  It is mastered in HD from a 4K scan. Sound is Dolby Digital.  There is no theatrical rating, but it is really viewable by everyone.  It is (1.85:1) anamorphic(fills the entire screen).  There are subtitles in English and chapter breaks to facilitate going to select parts of the film. The bonus material contains trailers from other films in the KL collection (licensed under Paramount Home Entertainment, Inc. as documented on the back of the case). I gave this a 4 star rating because, although the sound was crisp and clear, the instrumental music was set at much higher volume than the recorded dialog (typical of TV-style broadcasting that tries to draw you and keep your attention on the ads by making the ads louder than the show); a minor inconvenience that you can adjust yourself.  Have fun.  I did.
